\begin_layout Title
The Beta Expansion as a Dynamical System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepštas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
September 2020
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
linasvepstas@gmail.com
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
A beta-expansion is a representation of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{n}k_{n}\beta^{-n}$
\end_inset

 for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

 and a string of binary digits 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Such expansions are not unique, in general, and, for almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 there are an uncountable number of equivalent expansions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This text explores these classes of equivalent expansions.
 They can be organized into an infinite binary tree (whence uncountability).
 This tree induces a measure-preserving dynamical system, a subshift on
 the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is closely related to the subshift arising from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation is the iterated map 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta x\,\mod1$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting invariant measure (the Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron measure) is
 explored numerically and compared to the Renyi-Gelfond-Parry measure for
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation.
 The distance between branch-points in the infinite binary tree can be obtained
 from this measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform is the iterated map 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

 applied to the unit interval on the real number line.
 A very special case of this map is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

, which is named the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dyadic transform
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The dyadic transform is, in a certain sense, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

completely solvable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that it has been heavily studied and is well-understood.
 It's dynamics is described by the Bernoulli process.
 It is ergodic, and corresponds to a shift operator acting on the Cantor
 space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

: this is the shift that lops off one bit from an infinite bit-string.
 The shift can be expressed as a dynamical system; the dissipative part
 of the dynamical system is described by a transfer operator (the Ruelle-Frobeni
us-Perron operator) acting on the Borel algebra (sigma algebra) associated
 to the Cantor space.
 The spectrum of the transfer operator is discrete, when limited to the
 real-analytic functions; the spectrum is continuous when acting on square-integ
rable functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not as much is known for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\ne2$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform is still a shift, in that it can still be understood as a way
 of lopping off one bit from an infinite bit-string in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 However, not all possible bit-strings can occur; it is a subshift, in that
 there is a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subset\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform.
 Corresponding to this invariance is an invariant measure, first demonstrated
 by Renyi, and given explicit form by Gelfond and Parry.
 As an invariant measure, it is the eigenvalue-one (the Frobenius-Perron
 eigenvalue) eigenfunction of the transfer operator.
 The remaining spectrum of the transfer operator is poorly understood, but
 is explored by this author in a different text.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ve-Spect20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Understanding the dissipative spectrum is important, as it explicitly describes
 the rate of convergence of numerical explorations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cantor space can be mapped to the reals in the unit interval, by interpretin
g a bit-string in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 as a binary expansion of a real number.
 Famously, the mapping is surjective, in that the dyadic rationals have
 two inequivalent binary expansions: a dyadic rational can be written either
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{k}1000\cdots$
\end_inset

 ending in an infinite string of zeros, or as 
\begin_inset Formula $0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{k}0111\cdots$
\end_inset

 ending in an infinite string of one's.
 The dyadic rationals are in one-to-one correspondence with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the (conventional) Cantor set (the one with middle-thirds removed.) These
 gaps are also in one-to-one correspondence with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between the left-right subtrees in an infinite tree; they are also in one-to-on
e correspondence with the cusps of modular forms (as the infinite binary
 tree can be mapped into the modular group).
 For the general 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\ne2,$
\end_inset

the situation changes: rather than there being only two (in-)equivalent
 binary expansions, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 (that is, uncountably many) of them! This text is an exploration of these
 expansions for the general case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remainder of the introduction introduces all of the various basic ideas
 and notations pertinent to this system, followed by a short literature
 review.
 The introduction is written at a very low level of mathematical sophistication,
 and presumes almost no prior acquaintance with dynamical systems; this
 text is meant to be approachable by casual mathematical enthusiasts.
 After the introduction, the main results of this paper are presented; they
 are almost entirely grounded in a numerical exploration, as obtaining formal
 results is quite daunting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main results follow in order: the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be organized into an infinite binary tree; the locations of the branch
 points in the tree can be explicitly specified; the distance between branch-poi
nts can be explicitly stated.
 The specification of the branch-points induces a dynamical system; it has
 an invariant measure (which is not the Gelfond-Parry measure).
 The distances between branch-points can be directly related to this measure.
 The text terminates with a short conclusion and some speculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bernoulli shift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli shift (
\emph on
aka
\emph default
 the bit-shift map, the dyadic transform or the full shift) is an iterated
 map on the unit interval, given by iteration of the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b(x)=\begin{cases}
2x & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
2x-1 & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:Bernoulli shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The symbolic dynamics of this map gives the binary digit expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{n}(x)=(b\circ b\circ\cdots\circ b)(x)=b(b(\cdots b(x)\cdots))
\]

\end_inset

to denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold iteration of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{0}(x)=x$
\end_inset

.
 The symbolic dynamics is given by the bit-sequence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le b^{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le b^{n}(x)\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:bernoulli-bits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(Attention: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a subscript on the left, and a superscript on the right! The left is
 a sequence, the right is an iteration.
 Using the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 one both sides is a convenient abuse of notation.) Of course, the symbolic
 dynamics recreates the initial real number:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_{n}\left(x\right)2^{-n-1}\label{eq:homomorphism}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

All of this is just a fancy way of saying that a real number can be written
 in terms of it's base-2 binary expansion.
 That is, the binary digits for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=b_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli shift has many interesting properties, connecting it to the
 Cantor set and a large class of self-similar fractals.
 It is also connected to the modular group and elliptic functions (thence
 to number theory and Riemann surfaces).
 It is also the primary example of an ergodic system, and, in a sense, has
 far-reaching implications for ergodic systems via Ornstein theory.
 These various connections are far too numerous to review here, beyond these
 brief mentions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current task is to attempt to see how many of these properties still
 hold in the more general case of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Shift space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shift space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is formally defined to be a set of infinite sequences of a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 letters (or symbols), together with a shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 that takes each sequence, and lops off the left-most symbol.
 For the Bernoulli shift, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 letters, taken from the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For the Bernoulli shift, one is typically interested in the set of 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 possible infinite sequences: this is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 One writes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 for this shift space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 denoting countable infinity.
 For the Bernoulli shift, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the shift operator: it just lops of the left-most symbol.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, a shift space does not have to include every possible sequence
 of symbols; it does, however, by definition, have to be shift-invariant.
 That is, given some set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of infinite sequences of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 symbols, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a shift space if and only if, by loping off the leading symbol of each
 string, one regains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 again.
 That is, a shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 must obey 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TS=S
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left\{ 000\cdots,111\cdots\right\} $
\end_inset

 contains only two elements: the string of all zeros, and the string of
 all ones; loping off the leading digit just returns 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 again.
 In general, shift spaces may contain a finite, or a countable, or an uncountabl
e number of elements.
 In general, one defines the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as the space 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 of all possible strings of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 symbols.
 Subsets that are shift spaces are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

subshifts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The words 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

symbolic dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 also deserve some mention: given one specific sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 out of the shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, one can ponder 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

where it goes to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as one lops off a symbol at a time.
 This gives the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

symbolic dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the sequence.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

orbit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is defined as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ T^{m}x\,|\,\mbox{integer }m\ge0\right\} $
\end_inset

 – that is, the set of all places that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes to.
 There are several possibilities: one is that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a fixed point, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $Tx=x$
\end_inset

.
 Another is that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a repeating sequence of symbols, in which case iteration repeats as
 well: 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{m}x=x$
\end_inset

 holds whenever the repeat length is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

; this is a periodic orbit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most importantly, when there are non-periodic orbits, then there are uncountably
 many of them.
 That is, the number of periodic orbits is always countable: there are at
 most 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 starting points for an orbit, and they are of at most length 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 This includes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

eventually periodic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 orbits: those that begin with some finite initial sequence of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 moves, eventually settling into a periodic recurrence.
 This cannot be done for the non-periodic orbits: they cannot be placed
 in lexicographic order; as the Cantor slash argument applies.
 The non-periodic orbits are always uncountable.
 In this sense, the non-periodic orbits are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more important
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that the make up the bulk of all orbits.
 There are situations in which the periodic orbits can be said to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

govern
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the dynamics of the aperiodic ones; this is termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coherent structure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 However such concepts are advanced, and are not obviously applicable to
 the current situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Beta shift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta shift is similar to the Bernoulli shift, replacing the number 2
 by a constant real-number value 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

.
 It can be defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\beta}(x)=\begin{cases}
\beta x & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:downshift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Just as the Bernoulli shift generates a sequence of digits, so does the
 beta shift: write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{n}=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:down-bits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given the symbolic dynamics, one can reconstruct the original value whenever
 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{k_{0}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{1}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{2}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\cdots\right)\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Written this way, the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}(x)$
\end_inset

 clearly acts as a shift on this sequence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}(x)=\frac{k_{1}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{2}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{4}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\cdots\right)\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

In this sense, this shift is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exactly solvable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the above provides a closed-form solution for iterating and un-iterating
 the sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying out the above sequence, one obtains the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, namely the series
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{1}{2}\,\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{k_{n}}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:shift series}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, the bit-sequence that was extracted by iteration can be used to
 reconstruct the original real number.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

 in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bernoulli-bits"

\end_inset

 gives the Bernoulli shift: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}\left(x\right)=b\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the Bernoulli shift, not every possible bit-sequence occurs in this
 system.
 It is a subshift of the full shift: it is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 This is explored in greater detail in a later section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Density Visualizations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

long-term dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift can be visualized by means of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bifurcation diagram
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Scare quotes are used, as these are imprecise terms; greater precision
 will be provided shortly.
 The idea of a bifurcation diagram was made famous by the Feigenbaum map,
 and so the same idea is applied here: track orbits over long periods of
 time, and see where they go.
 This forms a density, which can be numerically explored by histogramming.
 This is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Undershift-Bifurcation-Diagram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When this is done for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift, one thing becomes immediately apparent: there are no actual 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bifurcations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

islands of stability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, no period-doubling regions, none of the stuff normally associated with
 the Feigenbaum map.
 Although there are periodic orbits, these form a set of measure zero: the
 iteration produces purely chaotic motion for almost all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>1$
\end_inset

.
 In this sense, the beta transform provides a clean form of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure chaos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Formal mathematics distinguishes between many different kinds of chaotic
 number sequences: those that are ergodic, those that are weakly or strongly
 Bernoulli, weakly or strongly mixing.
 The beta transform is known to be ergodic,
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Renyi57"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 weakly mixing
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and weakly Bernoulli.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dajani97"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 without the pesky 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

islands of stability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 popping up intermittently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The visualization of the long-term dynamics is done by generating a histogram,
 and then taking the limit, as follows.
 One divides the unit interval into a fixed sequence of equal-sized bins;
 say a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 bins, so that each is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 in width.
 Pick a starting 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and then iterate: if, at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th iteration, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $j/N\le b_{\beta}^{n}(x)<(j+1)/N$
\end_inset

, then increment the count for the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

'th bin.
 After a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 iterations, let 
\begin_inset Formula $c(j;M)$
\end_inset

 be the count in the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

'th bin.
 This count is the histogram.
 In the limit of a large number of iterations, as well as small bin sizes,
 one obtains a distribution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(y;x)=\lim_{N\to\infty}\lim_{M\to\infty}\frac{c(j;M)}{M}\mbox{ for }\frac{j}{N}\le y<\frac{j+1}{N}
\]

\end_inset

This distribution depends on the initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 chosen for the point to be iterated; a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution results when one averages over all starting points:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(y)=\int_{0}^{1}\rho(y;x)\,dx
\]

\end_inset

Numerically, this integration can be achieved by randomly sampling a large
 number of starting points.
 Observe that, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(y)$
