\begin_layout Section
Beta expansions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli process and it's relationship to the Cantor set provides the
 baseline to which the beta-shift can be compared.
 The beta-shift has a number of very striking differences, however, which
 manifest themselves in the structure of the beta-transformations.
 This section provides the main results being reported in this text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More precisely, again consider the binary expansion of a real number
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots
\]

\end_inset

The dyadic rationals, rationals in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\left(2k+1\right)/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 have two equivalent representations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{n-2}1000\cdots
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{n-2}0111\cdots
\]

\end_inset

These are equivalent as real numbers; they are inequivalent as elements
 of the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 flies to mind when one writes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{n}}{3^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

the collection of such real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 being the conventional Cantor set as it appears in the reals.
 It obviously has 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 These are the objects of study here.
 They have a natural interpretation in terms ot the infinite binary tree:
 a gap occurs whenever one makes a left-right decision in travelling down
 the tree.
 The left sub-tree is distinct from the right, and the gap is what lies
 in between.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is also interesting, as it suggests that the real numbers can be constructed
 from the Cantor set by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gluing together the gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: a nicely intuitive idea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This idea fits nicely with that of Lebesgue dimension.
 The Cantor space is zero-dimensional, in that every point in the Cantor
 space is covered by a single open set (a cylinder set), and every refinement
 of cylinder set is such that the point is contained in one set.
 This is because, in the product topology, all open sets are either disjoint,
 or are subsets of one-another.
 The real number line has Lebesgue covering dimension of one in the natural
 topology: refinements of open covers chain together.
 The double-membership, the double-expansion of the dyadic rationals can
 be understood as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

root source
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of why the real numbers have to be one dimensional.
\end_layout

