\begin_layout Standard
Glenndinning and Sidorov consider the conjugate problem: are there any points
 in the unit interval for which the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion is unique? The answer is that there are none, when 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le\varphi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\left(1+\sqrt{5}\right)/2$
\end_inset

 the Golden ratio; there are two when 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi<\beta\le\beta_{f}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{f}=1.7548776\cdots$
\end_inset

 is the root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{3}=2\beta^{2}-\beta+1$
\end_inset

, a countable number when 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{f}<\beta<\beta_{c}$
\end_inset

 and an uncountable number 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 (the cardinality of the Cantor set) when 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{c}\le\beta<2$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Glendinning01"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 The last accumulate towards 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{c}$
\end_inset

 is very interesting; lets call it the Komornik–Loreti number.
 It is a transcendental number built from the Thue–Morse sequence, having
 the approximate value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{c}=1.787231650\cdots$
\end_inset

 Above this number, there is only one unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 Although it plays this important role in the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansions, it does not seem to appear in any of the constructions in this
 text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The tree of expansions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 generated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is unique; one may wonder, where are all those other expansions hiding?
 The answer becomes apparent after some thought: they are the result of
 failing to take a 'mod 1' at certain times during the iteration.
 That is, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}^{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 obeys 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)<\beta/2$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can generate the desired gaps only if the input sequence breaks out of
 this bound at the cylinder locations 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 As there are an uncountable number of such locations for (almost) every
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then perhaps these accumulate to form a non-zero measure, extending beyond
 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This argument can be made more plausible if it can be shown that the spacing
 between the alternative expansion points tends to a constant.
 So, for example, if every fifth bit is a location where an alternative
 expansion can be made, then one might expect that one-fifth of the extended
 measure to fall outside the bound 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 This intuitive idea needs to be firmed up, as the expansion points are
 not merely points in a linear sequence, but are points in a binary tree.
 That is, the length of the branches in the tree must be measured, and averaged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Towards this end, let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 denote the infinite binary tree, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 denote a specific location on the tree.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is an index into the tree.
 The natural representation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is as a finite sequence of left-right moves.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a finite string of binary digits.
 Alternately, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a sequence of left-moves, followed by a mirror, and
 again some left moves, 
\emph on
etc.

\emph default
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}r\cdots rg^{a_{m}}$
\end_inset

 or, more compactly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=(a_{1},a_{2},\cdots,a_{m})$
\end_inset

 for integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 These are obviously the binary and the continued-fraction representations
 for a location on the tree.
 It is convenient to define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{len}:D\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{len}\gamma$
\end_inset

 to the number of left-right moves in 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{len}$
\end_inset

 just counts the depth into the tree; equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{len }\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the length of the string 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 (in the binary representation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p:D\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 be a function that assigns a natural number to each node on the binary
 tree.
 Such a function can be said to be strictly increasing if (and only if)
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\gamma^{\prime}\right)>p\left(\gamma\right)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{len}\gamma^{\prime}>\mbox{len}\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 For the present situation, we wish to take 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\gamma\right)$
\end_inset

 to be the distance to the branch point at 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 to be the length of the bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 where the branch is taken.
 The average distance between branch points is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l\left(\beta\right)=\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{1}{n+1}\sum_{\gamma:\mbox{len}\gamma\le n}\frac{p\left(\gamma L\right)+p\left(\gamma R\right)-2p\left(\gamma\right)}{2^{1+\mbox{len}\gamma}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma R$
\end_inset

 are the left and right locations under 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and the sum is limited to trees of depth 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Regrouping terms, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{n}\left(\beta\right)=\frac{1}{2^{n}}\sum_{\gamma:\mbox{len}\gamma=n}p\left(\gamma\right)
\]

\end_inset

