\begin_layout Subsection
Orbits, subshifts and measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The branch-points can be thought of as being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dense in the tree
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\left(\beta\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Intuitively, having dense branch-points suggests that the corresponding
 map should have a positive measure on the real number line.
 In this case, one then expects the out-of-bounds measure to be roughly
 proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\ell\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This can be made precise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each alternative expansion arises from an alternative orbit.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 specify that alternative; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a specific path down the binary tree.
 It is a sequence of left-right moves down the tree.
 Denote these moves as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\left(\gamma_{0},\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for a left-move and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}=1$
\end_inset

 for a right move.
 Correspondingly, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{0},p_{1},p_{2},\cdots)$
\end_inset

 be locations of the alternative choices in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion along that particular path.
 Given a walk 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 down the infinite tree, the alternative orbit for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is then given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{n}\left(x;\gamma\right)=\begin{cases}
T_{\beta}^{n}\left(x\right) & \mbox{ for }n<p_{0}\\
\left(1-\gamma_{0}\right)\beta T_{\beta}^{p_{0}-1}\left(x\right)+\gamma_{0}T_{\beta}^{p_{0}}\left(x\right) & \mbox{ for }n=p_{0}\\
T_{\beta}^{n-p_{0}}\left(\tau_{p_{0}}\left(x\right)\right) & \mbox{ for }p_{0}<n<p_{1}\\
\cdots & \cdots\\
\left(1-\gamma_{k}\right)\beta\tau_{n-1}\left(x\right)+\gamma_{k}T\left(\tau_{n-1}\left(x\right)\right) & \mbox{ for }n=p_{k}\\
T_{\beta}^{n-p_{k}}\left(\tau_{p_{k}}\left(x\right)\right) & \mbox{ for }p_{k}<n<p_{k+1}\\
\cdots & \cdots
\end{cases}\label{eq:expand-orbits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This orbit has a corresponding bit string expansion
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{n}\left(x;\gamma\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le\tau_{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\mbox{ and n\ensuremath{\ne p_{k}}}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le\tau_{n}(x)\le1\mbox{ and n\ensuremath{\ne p_{k}}}\\
\gamma_{k} & \mbox{ if }n=p_{k}
\end{cases}\label{eq:expand-path-bits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This bit-string is exactly the same as that of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:expanded bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, except that it uses a more precise notation for the path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, one has that each of these bit-strings provide an inequivalent
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion for the same 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, one has, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 (and almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

) that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{1}{2}\,\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\kappa_{n}\left(x;\gamma\right)}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:beta expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

by construction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the orbits 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{n}\left(x;\gamma\right)$
\end_inset

 are no longer confined to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\beta/2\right]$
\end_inset

, but can breifly venture outside of it.
 For any fixed path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, there are a countable number of such locations.
 However, there are an uncountable number of paths 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 down the tree, and so one might reasonably expect that these orbits accumulate
 on the real number line with a non-zero measure.
\end_layout

