 is surjective should be fairly obvious: if there was some bit-string 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 that could not be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $T\kappa^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 for some other 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{\prime}\in S^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, then the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion would be neither 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta x$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $TS^{\prime}=S^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 extends to an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 acting on cylinder sets.
 By the same argument, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{TS}^{\prime}=\mathcal{S}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 is an injection follows essentially from the properties of a sigma-algebra:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 preserves unions and intersections, so that if there were two different
 cylinder sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma,\sigma^{\prime}\in\mathcal{S}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\sigma=\mathcal{T}\sigma^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\backslash\sigma^{\prime}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}^{-1}:\mathcal{S^{\prime}\to\mathcal{S}^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One may now consider some space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 with elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 are maps 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{S^{\prime}}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 acts as a pushforward, defining a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 by composition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}f=f\circ\mathcal{T}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 As a linear operator, this has a spectrum.
 As it corresponds to a shift, the Frobenius-Perron theorem applies.
 The largest eigenvalue is some invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}:\mathcal{S^{\prime}}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}\mu_{\beta}=\mu_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 This measure can be taken to be the restriction of the Bernoulli measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 to the subalgebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 does not actually depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, only the subalgebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}^{\prime}=\mathcal{S}_{\beta}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 This holds likewise for the Renyi–Gelfond–Parry measure: it is just the
 usual Bernoulli measure restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 It looks unusual when mapped to the unit interval, but that is entirely
 because the mapping of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to the unit interval is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unusual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 I beleive that this is effectively an application of Ornstein theory to
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform.
 Ornstein theory basically just says that there is a large range of disparate
 phenomena, but that the underlying dynamics is that of the Bernoulli process;
 the phenomena look different only because they are obscured by different
 mappings from the Bernoulli process to the system in question.
