\begin_layout Subsection
Average distance from the invariant measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 between branching points is directly related to likelihood of encountering
 a one followed by 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 zero's in a given string.
 In a previous section, an average value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 was defined, but this was not quite correct, as the average was taken over
 a measure that was not shift-invariant.
 The measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 visualized in the last section is the appropriate measure.
 This follows, as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 contained only the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion strings, and the algebra of cylinders 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 inherited a shift-invariant weighting from the Bernoulli measure.
 Thus, each string in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 can now be counted uniformly, which allows averages of properties of strings
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 to be properly taken.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Distances are accessible via some simple considerations.
 Starting with any number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the first digit in the expansion will be a one if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}(x)\le1$
\end_inset

.
 A string of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 zeros follow if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le T_{\beta}^{j}(x)<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1<j\le m+1$
\end_inset

.
 The first condition is satisfied if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{\beta}\quad\mbox{ or }\quad\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\quad\mbox{or }\quad1+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le1+\frac{1}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

There are three pre-images, as the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is non-zero for values 
\begin_inset Formula $1<x$
\end_inset

.
 The second condition is satisfied if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\beta^{m}\left(T_{\beta}\left(x\right)-\frac{1}{2}\right)<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

; that is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}\left(x\right)<\frac{1}{2}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The intersection with the three intervals is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{2\beta}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right) & \quad\mbox{ or }\\
\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\beta}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right) & \quad\mbox{ or }\\
1+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le1+\frac{1}{2\beta}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The corresponding cylinders are to be sampled out of the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 of encountering such an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\beta\right)=\int_{a}^{b}d\mu_{\beta}+\int_{c}^{d}d\mu_{\beta}+\int_{e}^{f}d\mu_{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[c,d\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[e,f\right]$
\end_inset

 are the three pre-images above.
 This gives the expectation value for the distance between such cylinders:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{4/3}\ell\left(\beta\right)d\mu_{\beta}=\frac{1}{p\left(\beta\right)}
\]

\end_inset

(Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $4/3$
\end_inset

 is taken as an 
\emph on
ad hoc
\emph default
 value above which the measure always vanishes; more precisely, the upper
 bound is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi+1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 given by the 
\begin_inset Formula $m=2$
\end_inset

 transition; the actual upper bound depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The argument can also be rephrased in the language of physics.
 The distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\left(\beta\right)=\lim_{n\to\infty}\ell_{n}\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 has an a priori 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-dependence, and so, when considering the distance between branch points
 in a thermalized orbit, one must use the corresponding thermalized measure
 for sampling.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 priovides that thermalized measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Generalized Measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observation that the Renyi-Gelfond-Parry measure is just the Bernoulli
 measure restricted to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-subshift opens the door to playing games with the generalized measures.
 The general idea can be made more explicit.
 The Bernoulli measure on the full shift can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(b^{n}\left(1\right)-x\right)}{2^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Bernoulli shift given in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Bernoulli shift"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}\left(1\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(1-x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le1\le1$
\end_inset

 and thus the sum trivially leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 which is just the Bernoulli measure.
 The Renyi-Gelfond-Parry measure is just a rescaling.
 The orbit of 1 is no longer 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 but is 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 and the unit interval is not stretched out to twice the thinness but to
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

 of the thinness, and so one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(t^{n}\left(1\right)-x\right)}{\beta^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

up to a normalization constant 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

